measures.name: openstudio_results
measures.description: This measure creates high level tables and charts pulling both from model inputs and EnergyPlus results. It has building level information as well as detail on space types, thermal zones, HVAC systems, envelope characteristics, and economics. Click the heading above a chart to view a table of the chart data.
measures.modeler_description: For the most part consumption data comes from the tabular EnergyPlus results, however there are a few requests added for time series results. Space type and loop details come from the OpenStudio model. The code for this is modular, making it easy to use as a template for your own custom reports. The structure of the report uses bootstrap, and the graphs use dimple js.

arguments.name: units
arguments.display_name: Which Unit System do you want to use?

arguments.name: reg_monthly_details
arguments.display_name: Report monthly fuel and enduse breakdown to registerValue
arguments.description: This argument does not effect HTML file, instead it makes data from individal cells of monthly tables avaiable for machine readable values in the resulting OpenStudio Workflow file.

measures.name: timeseries_objective_function
measures.description: Creates Objective Function from Timeseries Data
measures.modeler_description: Creates Objective Function from Timeseries Data.  The measure applies a Norm at each timestep between the difference of CSV metered data and SQL model data. A timeseries plot can also be created.  Possible outputs are 'cvrmse', 'nmbe', 'simdata' = sum of the simulated data, 'csvdata' = sum of metered data, 'diff' = P Norm between the metered and simulated data if Norm is 1 or 2, else its just the Difference.

arguments.name: csv_name
arguments.display_name: Path to CSV file for the metered data
arguments.description: Path to CSV file including file name.

arguments.name: csv_time_header
arguments.description: CSV Time Header Value. Used to determine the timestamp column in the CSV file

arguments.name: csv_var
arguments.description: CSV variable name. Used to determine the variable column in the CSV file
arguments.default_value: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)

inputs.maximum: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)
inputs.minimum: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)
inputs.mean: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)
inputs.deltaX: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)
inputs.stdDev: Whole Building:Facility Total Electric Demand Power [W](TimeStep)

arguments.name: convert_data
arguments.description: Convert Units in Metered Data

arguments.name: csv_var_dn
arguments.description: CSV variable display name. Not yet Implemented

arguments.name: year
arguments.description: Is the Year in the csv data timestamp => mm:dd:yy or mm:dd (true/false)

arguments.name: seconds
arguments.description: Is the Seconds in the csv data timestamp => hh:mm:ss or hh:mm (true/false)

arguments.name: key_value
arguments.description: SQL key value for the SQL query to find the variable in the SQL file

arguments.name: timeseries_name
arguments.description: TimeSeries Name for the SQL query to find the variable in the SQL file

arguments.name: reporting_frequency
arguments.description: Reporting Frequency for SQL Query

arguments.name: environment_period
arguments.description: Environment Period for SQL query

arguments.name: norm
arguments.display_name: Norm of the difference of csv and sql
arguments.description: Norm of the difference of csv and sql. 1 is absolute value. 2 is euclidean distance. 3 is raw difference.

arguments.name: scale
arguments.display_name: Scale factor to apply to the difference
